loc: Kyoto City, Kyoto Prefecture (location very approximate, either low mountain or suburban region)
rmk:
Rather noisy suburban environment (distant noise of garden management).
I noticed the unfamiliar two-note call (such as 0:00 and 0:04) and the bird suddenly
popped up to a power line.  The yellow part in the underparts extended
lower than typical Ficedula narcissina and the impression of the color
pattern was almost Motacilla cinerea.  Unfortunately the upper part
of the body was hidden and the bird was quicker than I could focus the camera.
The environment was more open than where Ficedula narcissina is
typically found.  The trills (such as 0:01 and 0:18) are typical of
a Ficedula species.  Soft calls at 0:22 (final two notes).
The unfamiliar call was probably a part of developing song
(like the fourth note in XC79623).
The same bird also issued more familiar calls (such as 0:07 and 0:17).
Based on the visual impression and call-song different from that of
Ficedula narcissina, I consider this species most likely.
See also partial song in XC469930.
The season well matches the peak migration of this species.

loc: University of Chinese Academy of Science, Yanqi Lake Campus, Beijing
Lvshuiwan Wetland Park (near  Nan Jing Shi), Jiang Su Sheng

rmk: I was watching a male and a female Yellow-rumped Flycatcher Ficedula zanthopygia actively feeding on the the fruit of the Macaranga bancana. There was competitive feeding with other Flycatchers and other birds especially the Green-backed Flycatchers Ficedula elisae. Fruit is taken by aerial sallies or hover-snatching, returning to a new perch each time. Interestingly the male Yellow-rumped Flycatcher was intermittently vocal – something I have not observed in the past (unlike Green-backed Flycatchers which often vocalise at migration sites). The calls were single notes uttered 1.5-2 seconds part. There appeared be another Yellow-rumped Flycatcher responding at times, perhaps the female.
